\end{center}

Figure 5. Calculated bulk moduli of lithiated silicon and lithiated $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ plotted against the degree of lithiation of these amorphous structures. Error bars correspond to the different configurations of the amorphous structure.

\section{Electrochemical impedance and cycling}
To obtain further insight into the chemical reactivity of $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ composite films, a 50nm thick sample was assembled into a coin cell and investigated by impedance spectroscopy and by galvanostatic charge and discharge measurements (Figure 6). Capacity is not normalized in this work since all the films have the same thickness and area. As shown in Figure $6 a$, a low amount of lithium could be extracted from the film even up to $1.5 \mathrm{~V}$ during the first charge cycle. This high OCV is due to the lower electrochemical potential of lithium in $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ which has part of lithium bonded with oxygen. To investigate the reaction of the $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ composite film with electrolyte, it was measured by AC impedance at the open circuit voltage, as shown in Figure $6 \mathrm{~b}$. When the $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ composite film comes into contact with electrolyte, the charge transfer resistance increases with time. In contrast, for the silicon electrode the impedance is not time dependent at open circuit voltage.\\
\includegraphics[max width=\textwidth, center]{2023_09_22_9a007c3865721f379b39g-15_472_1056_360_1776}

Figure 6. a) Voltage profile of lithium-rich $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ composite film and silicon-rich $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ composite film; b) Impedance evolution of lithium-rich $\mathrm{Li}_{\mathrm{x}} \mathrm{SiO}_{\mathrm{y}}$ composite and siliconrich $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ composite as well as Si film.

The higher charge transfer resistance of $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$, as compared to $\mathrm{Si}$, is likely to originate from the resulting $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ surface-electrolyte interface. The higher the lithium concentration in the compound, the lower the potential vs. lithium, which promotes reduction reactions with the electrolyte. During charging, as $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ is lithiated to $\mathrm{LixSiOy}$, this increased reactivity may lead to further consumption of electrolyte if $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ is exposed and not fully covered with the other chemically stable electrolyte decomposition products. There has been literature ${ }^{30}$ discussing reduction mechanisms of ethylene carbonate on the lithium silicide surface which identify different mechanisms depending on the degree of lithiation. Higher concentration of lithium was found to be more reactive due to the explicit interaction of $\mathrm{EC}$ molecules with $\mathrm{Li}^{+}$ions at the surface. In addition, recent experiment work by our group found that both lithium silicide and lithium silicate react with electrolyte, and form fluoride and carbonate species which are commonly seen in the SEI components. ${ }^{31-32}$ Computational work also demonstrate that chemistrydependent interaction happens on the surface of lithium silicide with electrolyte. ${ }^{33} \mathrm{We}$ note that increased lithiation of $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ leads to increased reactivity with the electrolyte, and consumes lithium inventory.

Impedance of the as-prepared $\mathrm{Li}_{\mathrm{x}} \mathrm{SiO}_{\mathrm{y}}$ thin film on interdigitated electrode (without any electrolyte exposure) is shown in Figure S5. This thin film behaves like a pure resistor, which is mainly due to the existence of lithium silicide in the film. Total conductivity is dominated by electronic conductivity. The total conductivity of a LixSiOy thin film is calculated as

\[
\sigma=\mathrm{L} /\left(\mathrm{R}^{*} \mathrm{~A}\right)
\]

where $\sigma$ is the conductivity, $\mathrm{L}$ is the distance between the $\mathrm{Pt}$ digits and $\mathrm{A}$ is the total contacting area. The conductivity $\sigma$ is calculated to be $2.7 \mathrm{~S} / \mathrm{cm}$, which is too high to be a good SEI layer.

To correlate the measured $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ properties with the electrochemical cycling performance of an electrode with $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ at the surface, a double layer sample was deposited with $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ on top of a silicon thin film, and compared to a Si film. The thickness of $\mathrm{Li}_{\mathrm{x}} \mathrm{SiO}_{\mathrm{y}}$ was set to $10 \mathrm{~nm}$ to emulate the native oxide thickness, and the thickness of silicon thin film was set to $50 \mathrm{~nm}$, as shown in the inset in Figure 7a. As shown in Figure 7a, during the first cycle discharge profile, $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y} / \mathrm{Si}$ exhibited a lower OCV of only $1.5 \mathrm{~V}$ (comparted to $2.5 \mathrm{~V}$ for $\mathrm{Si}$ ), due to the existing lithium on the silicon surface. The difference of the CV profiles above $0.25 \mathrm{~V}$ (before Si starts lithiating) results from the surface reaction between $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ and electrolyte. Both low potential of $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ and its reaction products make the electrochemical reduction different than that in the silicon case. The lower potential range profiles for both films are very similar, since the same thickness of silicon film was deposited. The cycling of $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y} / \mathrm{Si}$ showed a lower columbic efficiency and less stable performance as compared to the bare silicon (see Figure 7b). We note that the columbic efficiency of silicon is higher than that of the $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ -coated $\mathrm{Si}$, indicating that the $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ film exhibits a greater reactivity with electrolyte. We hypothesize that the $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ composite film continuously reacts with the electrolyte, preventing the stabilization of the SEI on the silicon electrode. These results suggest that $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ does not help stabilize the surface of the $\mathrm{Si}$ electrode, as the lithiation products are not stable upon cycling. Previously, there has been study ${ }^{34}$ the effect of $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ with various thickness from $2 \mathrm{~nm}, 7 \mathrm{~nm}$ to $10 \mathrm{~nm}$. Only the $7 \mathrm{~nm} \mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ coated $\mathrm{Si}$ showed the improved performance compared to Si. This is a complimentary result from both mechanical property and reactivity. More studies of the reactant product between $\mathrm{Li}_{\mathrm{x}} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ and electrolyte are in progress to clarify the role of $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ in the functionality and SEI stabilization of the Si anode.\\
\includegraphics[max width=\textwidth, center]{2023_09_22_9a007c3865721f379b39g-18_263_843_326_1786}

Figure 7. a) Charge and discharge profile of $\mathrm{Si}$ and $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y} / \mathrm{Si}$, with inset picture shows the schematic of double layer thin film; b) Cycle performance and Columbic efficiency of double layer thin film and pure silicon.

\section{Conclusions}
In summary, mechanical and electrochemical properties, as well as the chemical reactivity of the $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ composite thin film with $\mathrm{Li}$ to $\mathrm{Si}$ ratio between $1.7$ and $1.1$ were investigated. These $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ films with $\mathrm{Li}$-rich and Si-rich compositions were prepared by combinatorial sputtering, as a model system to study the initial products of lithiation of native oxide $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ layer on a $\mathrm{Si}$ anode, relevant for next-generation Li-ion batteries. Firstprinciples computational results show that both lithiated silicon and lithiated $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$ transition from brittle to ductile behavior as lithiation happens. The as-synthesized composite $\mathrm{Li}_{x} \mathrm{SiO}_{y}$ film, which is a mixture of lithium silicides and lithium silicates, shows an equivalent brittle to ductile transition. The intermediate product of lithiated $\mathrm{SiO}_{2}$, which contains lithium silicates and lithium silicates, is highly reactive with the electrolyte, due to the low potential resulting from high lithium content. These composite $\mathrm{Li}_{\mathrm{x}} \mathrm{SiO}_{\mathrm{y}}$ with $\mathrm{Li} / \mathrm{Si}=1.7$ and $\mathrm{Li} / \mathrm{Si}=1.1$ showed low electronic resistance and did not facilitate the passivation and stabilization of the Si films, despite their low resistance to fracture. Thus, a favorable ductile mechanical property is found to be a desirable but insufficient criterion for stable SEI formation; low chemical reactivity and low electronic conductivity are also important for stable electrodes.

